ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Only licence-fee funding can guarantee a BBC of sufficient scale </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and scope</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. Funding from the licence fee should be protect</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ed for use by core BBC services </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and not diverted to other purposes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">UK citizens are currently under-served by the mainstream media with international content</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The quantity </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and range of original </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">non-news </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">international </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">programming </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">on the PSB’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">has been steadily diminishing </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is now </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">owest level since 1989</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">        </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">IBT: </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> &amp; Reason for Submitting Evidence</span></p><h3 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> is a coalition of the UK’s international development agencies. IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">'s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">members</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">which are supported by a large proportion of the UK public, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">concerned with the effects of ‘globalisation’ and with communicating across the world.</span></h3><h3 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:113%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">One</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">aspect of the convergence era is that a ‘global</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> information society’ has be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">en </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">created in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">which we are all citizens. Communication</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> has</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> become global; and information exchange has become a primary driver of economics, politics and social interaction. </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> wants to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">citizens of this global information society </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> UK public </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is engaged </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nformation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">about the wider world</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Events and processes taking place </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">globally</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> affect all aspects of our lives: our security, economic prospects and well-being, health, education and training, our environment, and so on.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> being i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nfo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rmed </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">about the world; being able to participate as citizens in democratic debate about our own and our country’s role in the world; being empowered to have dialogue and connections with people and communities around the world – all these are becoming part </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of the basic ‘tool kit’ of citizenship. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Live television viewing has remained </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">relatively </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">stable </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in recent years </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">despite the proliferation of online media. 79% of people use television</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> news as their main source of information about the world, with only 8% relying on the internet, 5% on radio and 4% on newspapers. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Television news is consistently rated as the most important purpose of public service broadcasting – 81% of adults rank this </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">as the highest priority.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT argues that we need more than just news to engage us and inform us about the wider world because </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">news provides</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> an ex</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">emely narrow range of knowledge,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> given that most international news stories are overw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">helmingly a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">bout conflict and disasters</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Within television, it is the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ublic </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ervice </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">roadcasters</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(PSB’s) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">which have</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tatutory</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> responsibilities </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(Communications Act 2003) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to provide ‘information and education’ </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to provide a range of programmes on ‘matters of international significance or interest’. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">However s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ince 2005 there has been a drop</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of 41% </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">original </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">non-news international programming on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">main </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">PSB</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> channels</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and therefore the role of the BBC becomes all</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the more important to citizens as the princip</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> provider of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">hi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">gh quality information and knowledge about the wider world. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">96% of the UK public use the BBC each week and it remains the most important Public Service Broadcaster in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> 3. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What should </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Public service broadcasting refers to TV programmes that are broadcast for the public benefit rather than for purely commercial purposes.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> (Ofcom)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="a2"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Ofcom</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">measures delivery of prog</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ramming by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">public service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> broadcasters</span></a><a name="n7"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> against four objectives, or "public service purposes": (i) informing our understanding of the world; (ii) stimulating knowledge and learning; (iii) reflecting UK cultural identity; and (iv) representing diversity and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">alternative viewpoints.</span><a name="n8"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> IBT supports these criteria of measurement and believes they are still fit for purpose. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">What is the BBC for?</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Building Public Value,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the policy document </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the BBC published prior to the last Charter Renewal, the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">reaffirmed the original ambitions of those who had founded the organisation:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The BBC’s founders believed that broadcasting could make the world a better place. Public intervention would ensure that its astonishing creative power– to enrich individuals with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> knowledge, culture and information about their world, to build more cohesive communities, to engage the people of the UK and the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">whole globe in a new conversation about who we are and where we are going – would be put to work to the sole benefit of the pu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">blic.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">These are high ambitions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> IBT supports</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. We </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">believe the BBC needs to continue to take an ambitious, original, distinctive approach to public service content which appeals to a wide audience</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in order to maintain its reach</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT believes that the BBC should continue to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">aim to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">broadcast a high quality, inclusive service which is free at the point of access</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, is ambitious and risk-taking</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">valued </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">around the world. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Without the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> BBC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> our general levels of knowledge, understandi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ng, literacy and well-being would be considerably lower. And</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> as an example of what economists have referred to as ‘merit goods’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> BBC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> contribute</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to the general well-being of society as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s well as me</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">eting the needs of individuals</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> contr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ibute</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to economic development and to the creative industr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in Britain. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT’s primary concern is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">broadcast of high quality, mainstream </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">content which engages us with international issues</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and our submission will focus on this aspect of BBC delivery</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is IBT’s view that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">all BBC content should have an inherently global perspective </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in order to reflect the UK’s role in the world and our posi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tion as global citizens. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Thus international content should be supported by all the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">public purposes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">With reference to the global purpose, B</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, the Agreement which accompanies the charter states:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.8pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">developing (and reviewing) the purpose remit for bringing the UK to the world and the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">world to the UK, the Trust must, amongst other things, seek to ensure that the BBC—</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">makes people in the UK aware of international issues and of the different cultures</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">viewpoints of people living outside the UK through news and current affairs and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">other outputs such as drama, comedy, documentaries, educational output and sports</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">coverage; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">brings high-quality international news coverage to international audiences.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and its sister organisation 3WE activel</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">y participated in</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">2006</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Charter Renewal </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">process </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and contributed evidence which was instrumental in changing the wording of this purpose remit to include </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">bringing the world to the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Since then we have worked with the BBC Trust, submitting evidence to Licence Reviews and regularly meeting with Trustees, to ensure delivery of this purpose. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s international non-news output in recent years has, in our view, improved with series suc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">h as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Toughest Place to be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">…, Simon Reeve’s programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This World</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Panorama</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> – to name but a few - all making significant contributions to our understanding of other places, peoples and cultures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> right ones? How might they change?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is IBT’s view that the public purposes are the right ones. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The BBC exists as a conscious democratic, social and cultural intervention in the market in order to achieve certain </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">public value </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">purposes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">digital </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">era</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">many households have access to a wide range of sources of information and entertainment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, ho</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">wever </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">many of these come at a significant cost for consumers. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In this situation the provision of a basic package of high quality services for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> homes becomes a high priority for reasons of social equity, cultural cohesion, educational development and employabi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">lity. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The BBC should lead the way in providing </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">public service </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">content </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t needs to be of a scale and size to be able to take risks, to be innovative and to engage the public </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> creative, imaginative content which commercial broadcasters may not</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> because they have the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">needs of their shareholders in mind. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">One aspect where the BBC’s provision is distinctive and provides public value is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">news, especially the BBC’s provision of international news. I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">f the BBC is not able to maintain the scale</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of its current operation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> which has been significantly reduced </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">since</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the Delivering Quality First programme was introduced, the quality and range of its service</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ill </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">be undermined. Currently t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he BBC h</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">as a large enough reach </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the majority</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> people will see and hear its news and other information; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">can maintain a comprehensive establishment of international bureaux and correspondents; and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">can afford to invest the additional resources sometimes required by international filming assignment</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Without </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">investment in its news operation, its audiences w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ill</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> fall and a cycle w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ill</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> begin whereby BBC news w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ill</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> become less respected and deemed less important and therefore further cuts could follow. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Commercial publishers, rivals and opponents of the BBC criticise the scale and scope of the BBC’s intervention </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">especially </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the online market. Commercial operators </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> market failure is impossible</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in this choice-rich marketplace</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In this context</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would assert that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">arket failure’ does not simply refer to whether or not there are other providers in the marketplace. It</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> should</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> refer to the fact that, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">whatever the number of providers in the market at any given time, the market may still fail the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> citizen.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> This is because</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">if consumers are unwilling </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">or unable </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to pay for high quality information, producers will cease to invest in producing it, tending to reduce choice even where there is a multiplicity of providers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Should the BBC’s output and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">services be provided to any greater or lesser</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">degree for particular audiences? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT believes that the BBC needs to engage as wide an audience as possible across all its services. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e ambition based on the three pillars of universality, fairness and equity and accountability </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is explicitly stated in the Building Public Value BBC policy document in 2004:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘politicians and the public decided very early on that broadcasting should be plac</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ed in the public sphere of our national life. They believed that everyone has a right to high quality broadcast services, regardless of income, age, sex, race, religion or where they live. This is why the BBC was founded according to three public principle</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s which are common to many other staples of the nation’s public life – the UK’s public health and education systems, our public parks, our museums and libraries</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces in-house, commissions externally a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nd leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The BBC should continue to produce programmes across all genres. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT believes the current arrangement with quotas for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">independent production and the W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">indow of Creative Competition (W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">OCC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> are working well to ensure a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> thriving UK production sector as well as maintaining production and skills within the BBC. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9.   </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT believes the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fit with the public purposes and have achieved an adequate return</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> for licence fee payers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rom its 2012/13 figures it is clear </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">BBC Worldwide</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> is providing the BBC with extra revenue and it appears to be growing with headline p</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rofit </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">up 1% in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">2012/13. Since 2007 BBC Worldwide has provided </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">total returns to the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> over £1bn</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">We believe that BBC W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">orldwide’s activities should continue beyond 2016 following the same purposes and methods. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> ‘sixth public purpose’ of the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In promoting its other </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">purposes, helping to deliver to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services and, in addition, taking a leading role in the switchover to digital television</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT stated </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">its opposition to the BBC funding DSO </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in its submission </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to the Government’s Green Paper </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">on the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in 2004,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Paying for vulnerable users to switch to digital TV appears to us to be the responsibility of government rather than the BBC. It is part of the nation’s social and cultural policy rather than a responsibility of a single broadcaster. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 56.7pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Not only will other b</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">roadcasters, including those with very limited public service obligations, benefit from such schemes; but it will also mean diverting licence fee income, contributed by citizens to run the BBC, rather than using general taxation, which is paid in order to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">support, among other things, infrastructure development and social welfare.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.89pt; padding-left:3.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT’s position on this </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">issue</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> has not changed</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> since 2004</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> BBC should research future technology and the distribution of content </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">where that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">research </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">promotes its other purposes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is IBT’s view that the licence fee which is paid by the UK public for BBC content and services should not be diverted to pay for other responsibilities, such as the roll out of broadband infrastructure which is the responsi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">bility of the Government. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">11. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016? </span><br /><span style="border-color:#000000; border-style:solid; border-width:0.5pt; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The BBC should continue to be funded by the licence fee which should </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rise</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in line with RPI. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The basis for the BBC’s independence</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> from political interference</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> has, arguably, been the method of its funding. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Public support for the licence fee as the best option for funding the BBC is higher than it is for any other form of funding. </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">12. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there a case for distributing funding for public service content more</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">idely</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT does not believe there should be a separate distribution of funds for public service content beyond the funding provided to the BBC. The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and other public service broadcasters should continue to commission public service content from </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">independent producers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> which is a form of distribution of funding for public service content in itself</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT does not support the licence fee settlement reached in December 2011 by the current Government</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> because it </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">iverted</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> money from BBC budgets for progr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">amme</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">making</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> type of ‘top-slicing’ of licence fee </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">fun</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ding </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">undermines the direct relationship between the licence fee payer and the BBC. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">If this relationship is undermined by the Government </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">diverting</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the funding to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> pay for other purposes, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">trust betwee</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n the licence fee payer and the BBC is diminished. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">believes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> that no such licence fee settlements </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> conducted in future without a full public consultation, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">giving </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">licence fee payers </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">their say</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> over the funding they provide.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">13. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">As outlined in the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Building Public Value</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> document produced by the BBC in 2004 </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT believes </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">we should be wary of turning the BBC into the American model, where PB</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">S has become a minority service. This would inevitably happen if the BBC were forced to only broadcast programmes other channels will not.  While it shouldn’t be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">slave to ratings, it has to maintain its popularity in order to maintain its reach:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">why PBS, the sole American public service television</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">broadcaster, is a marginal broadcaster showing minority programmes in which</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">commercial television has no interest. It achieves a primetime viewing share of less</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">than 2%1. US television is essentially com</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mercial, funded either by advertising or by</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">subscription.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">14. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">hile </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> broadly support</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the current structure </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of regulation for the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, IBT has been as concerned as everyone else at recent </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">reports of expe</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">diture on executive pay</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT has been impressed with the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">BBC Trust’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Service Reviews conducted to monitor BBC output over the past 6 years. We believe that the BBC Trust has not been ‘</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">soft’ on the Executive and has spoken out where appropriate to ensure that BBC staff focus their energies on delivering the public purposes as set out in the Charter. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 31.73pt; padding-left:4.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">We welcomed </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">comments by the Secretary of State, Maria Miller, when she said the B</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">BC needs to focus on immediate issues which need to be resolved</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, “</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The immediate priority is that the BBC gets its house in order. Obviously the charter review is in 2016 and all of these other issues I’m sure will be part of that. But we should not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">distract away from the most important thing at the moment and we should not let other things get in the way”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Therefore IBT does not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">want to make any </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">comments on the governance of the BBC prior to the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">outcome</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> of the current Governance Review which </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is being conducted jointly by the BBC and the BBC Trust. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">15. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he BBC?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">IBT supports the constitutional framework of a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Ofcom PSB Report (2012).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt"> Building Public Value, 2004, BBC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">Research published by YouGov this year shows a similar pattern of results when people are asked to select their preferred means of funding the BBC with 48% backing the licence fee; 27% for advertising; 13% for subscription-only; and 6% a combination of adv</span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt">ertising and subscription. </span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Gill Sans'; font-size:6pt; font-style:italic">YouGov for Prospect, 1,712 GB adults 18+, February 2013 (online survey)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt"> Building Public Value, BBC, 2004</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="color:#000080; font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt"> Interview in The House Magazine, 22 November 2013</span></p></body></html>